'''Comas Sola''' (sometimes as '''Comas Solá''') is an [[impact crater]] on [[Mars]], located in the [[Memnonia quadrangle]] at 19.59°S latitude and 168.51°W longitude, and is inside [[Terra Sirenum]]. It measures {{cvt|120.24|km}} in diameter and was named after the Spanish [[Catalans|Catalan]] astronomer [[Josep Comas Solá]]. The name was approved by [[International Astronomical Union|IAU's]] [[Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|title= Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature: Comas Sola |url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/1276|website=usgs.gov |publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]] |accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>

Nearby named prominent craters include [[Burton (Martian crater)|Burton]] to the north-northeast, [[Bernard (Martian crater)|Bernard]] to the southeast, [[Dejnev (crater)|Dejnev]] to the southwest, almost to the west is [[Williams (Martian crater)|Williams]], nearly the same size and northwest not far from the crater is the tiny Gratteri.

Surrounding the southerm rim are two smaller unnamed craters, each with a central peak or mount, with the southwest touching the southwest rim, in the north rim, three tiny craters which also has a central mound. Almost touching the crater are a series of rilles and rifts known as [[Memnonia Fossae]] that were once fault lines

