__NOTOC__ {{Chinese |t=扎馬魯丁<ref>{{harvnb|Zhu|Fuchs|1946|p=3}}</ref> |p=Zhámălúdīng |lang2=fa |lang2_content=جمال الدين محمد بن طاهر بن محمد الزيدي البخاري }}
'''Jamal ad-Din Muḥammad ibn Ṭāhir ibn Muḥammad al‐Zaydī al‐Bukhārī''' (variously [[Persian transcription|transcribed]] '''Jamal ud-Din''', '''Jamal al-Din''' ({{abbr|lit.|literally}} [[Jamal|Beauty]] of Faith), etc., Chinese name '''Zhamaluding''') was a 13th-century [[Persian people|Persian]]<ref>{{cite web|author1=Liu Yingsheng|author2=Peter Jackson|last-author-amp=yes|title=CHINESE-IRANIAN RELATIONS iii. Mongol Period – Encyclopaedia Iranica|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/chinese-iranian-iii|website=www.iranicaonline.org|publisher=Encyclopedia Iranica|accessdate=11 February 2017|language=en|quote=A Persian astronomer named Jamāl-al-Dīn Boḵārī, who had already visited China in the time of Möngke...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Selin|first1=Hrsg. H.|title=Encyclopaedia of the History of Science, Technology, and Medicine in Non-Western Cultures|date=2006|publisher=Springer Netherland|location=Berlin|isbn=978-1-4020-4559-2|page=1143|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref name="Rossabi2014">{{cite book|author=Morris Rossabi|title=From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXejBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA229&lpg=PA229#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=28 November 2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-28529-3|pages=229–}}</ref> [[astronomer]]. Originally from [[Bukhara]], he entered the service of [[Kublai Khan]] around the 1250s to set up an Islamic Astronomical Bureau in his new capital [[Beijing]], to operate in parallel with the traditional Chinese bureau.<ref>{{harvnb|van Dalen|2007}}</ref> Kublai Khan thus maintained the bureaucratic structure, but allowed Chinese observations and predictions to be checked by respected Muslim scholars.
He is credited with having taken seven astronomical instruments to Kublai Khan, as a present from [[Hulagu Khan]] including a Persian [[astrolabe]], a [[globe]] and an [[armillary sphere]], in 1267.<ref>{{harvnb|Zhu|Fuchs|1946|p=4}}</ref><ref name="Rossabi2014 1">{{cite book|author=Morris Rossabi|title=From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXejBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA281&lpg=PA281#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=28 November 2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-28529-3|pages=281–}}</ref> This is the earliest known reference to a spherical terrestrial globe of the Earth in [[Chinese astronomy]].<ref>{{citation|title=The Image of the Spherical Earth|author=David Woodward|journal=[[Perspecta (journal)|Perspecta]]|volume=25|year=1989|pages=3–15 [9]|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|jstor=1567135}}</ref><ref> {{citation|title=[[Science and Civilisation in China]]|volume=3|first=Joseph |last=Needham|year=1959|page=376}} </ref>
He is associated with a [[zij]] in Persian which has been lost but was translated into Chinese in 1383 by [[Ma‐shayihei]] with the title ''Huihuilifa'' (Islamic calendar). This contained [[Ptolemy|Ptolomaic]] tables based on new values and adjusted to Beijing and has been reconstructed in recent years.<ref>{{harvnb|van Dalen|2007}}</ref>
In general, his activity didn't make much difference to Chinese astronomy. However [[Guo Shoujing]]<ref name="Rossabi2014 2">{{cite book|author=Morris Rossabi|title=From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXejBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA282&lpg=PA282#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=28 November 2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-28529-3|pages=282–}}</ref> did evidently gain the idea of the [[torquetum]] from him (which he didn't bring), and produced a simplified version which omitted ecliptic coordinates which were not used in China.<ref>{{harvnb|Needham|1959|p=375}}</ref>
In 1286 he carried out a large-scale survey of the Yuan empire which was produced in 755 volumes as the ''Dayitongzh''. All but the introduction of this has been lost.<ref>{{harvnb|van Dalen|2007}}</ref>
